SIMPLE: different
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Different
<hw>Dif"fer*ent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>differens</ets>, <ets>-entis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>differre</ets>:
cf. F. <ets>diff⟦eacute⟧rent</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Distinct;
separate; not the same; other.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Five <xex>different</xex>
churches.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of various or contrary nature, form, or quality;
partially or totally unlike; dissimilar; <as>as, <ex>different</ex>
kinds of food or drink; <ex>different</ex> states of health;
<ex>different</ex> shapes; <ex>different</ex> degrees of
excellence.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men are as <qex>different</qex> from each other, as the regions in
which they are born are <qex>different</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <ex>Different</ex> is properly followed by
<xex>from</xex>. <xex>Different to</xex>, for <xex>different from</xex>,
is a common English colloquialism. <xex>Different than</xex> is quite
inadmissible.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>differentia</ent>⟦br⟧
